674. Eur J Surg Oncol. 1992 Jun;18(3):224-9.

Ki67 immunoreactivity in breast carcinoma: relationships to prognostic variables 
and short term survival.

Locker AP(1), Birrell K, Bell JA, Nicholson RI, Elston CW, Blamey RW, Ellis IO.

Author information:
(1)Nottingham City Hospital, Cardiff, UK.

Immunoreactivity of the monoclonal antibody Ki67, which recognizes an antigen 
expressed in cells active in the cell cycle, has been investigated by 
immunocytochemistry in a series of 67 primary breast cancers. The percentage of 
tumour cell nuclei stained by Ki67 (labelling index) was related to tumour 
histological grade, mitotic frequency, oestrogen receptor status and tumour 
type. No correlation was found with patient age, tumour size or lymph node 
stage. A high Ki67 labelling index was significantly associated with diminished 
patient survival and disease-free interval, which demonstrates an important role 
for this monoclonal antibody as a prognostic marker in breast cancer.

