681. J Arthroplasty. 1992 Jun;7(2):183-6. doi: 10.1016/0883-5403(92)90014-h.

Life expectancy after total hip arthroplasty.

Holmberg S(1).

Author information:
(1)Department of Orthopaedics, Samaritan Hospital, Uppsala, Sweden.

The 6-year survival rate was investigated in 646 patients undergoing total hip 
arthroplasty for osteoarthritis, rheumatoid arthritis, or complications 
following femoral neck fracture between 1978 and 1982. A comparison of mortality 
was done between patients treated by osteosynthesis for fresh femoral neck 
fracture and a matched general population. The mortality was lower than that of 
the matched general population after total hip arthroplasty and even lower for 
patients treated for fresh femoral neck fracture. Patients undergoing total hip 
arthroplasty for osteoarthritis had the highest survival rate, followed by 
patients with rheumatoid arthritis and complications after femoral neck 
fractures.

