683. J Rheumatol. 1992 May;19(5):704-8.

Life table analysis of 879 treatment episodes with slow acting antirheumatic 
drugs in community rheumatology practice.

Morand EF(1), McCloud PI, Littlejohn GO.

Author information:
(1)Rheumatology Unit, Monash Medical Centre, Clayton, Victoria, Australia.

Erratum in
    J Rheumatol 1992 Dec;19(12):1998.

In 596 patients with RA managed over a decade in a community practice setting, 
879 slow acting antirheumatic drug (SAARD) treatment episodes were analyzed 
using 5-year life tables. The probability of continuation of therapy was 50% by 
9-24 months for all drugs except for methotrexate (MTX), which was 62% by 5 
years [corrected]. MTX treatments were of significantly longer duration than 
those of all other SAARD (p less than 0.001); terminations for both inefficacy 
(p less than 0.001) and toxicity (NS) were less likely. These findings concur 
with recent evidence suggesting that MTX is a superior SAARD in this setting.

